1
00:00:05,539 --> 00:00:06,751
Hello, everyone.

2
00:00:06,759 --> 00:00:11,998
In this video, let's address
the subject of suborbital spaceflight,

3
00:00:11,999 --> 00:00:15,539
which nowadays is performed
mainly by commercial companies.

4
00:00:16,525 --> 00:00:19,574
The definition
of a suborbital spaceflight,

5
00:00:19,575 --> 00:00:22,824
it's a flight in which
the spacecraft reaches space,

6
00:00:22,825 --> 00:00:25,584
which is more 
than 100 kilometers altitude

7
00:00:25,585 --> 00:00:26,794
in the case of the Earth.

8
00:00:26,795 --> 00:00:28,543
This is the so-called Kármán line,

9
00:00:28,544 --> 00:00:33,273
the boundary between aeronautics
below 100 kilometers

10
00:00:33,274 --> 00:00:35,814
and astronautics above 100 kilometers.

11
00:00:36,242 --> 00:00:38,992
If you go above 100 kilometers,
you have gone into space.

12
00:00:39,542 --> 00:00:41,291
And the case of suborbital,

13
00:00:41,292 --> 00:00:45,031
the trajectory of the spacecraft
intersects the atmosphere

14
00:00:45,032 --> 00:00:47,602
or the surface of the body
from which it was launched.

15
00:00:48,173 --> 00:00:50,262
So it does not even complete one orbit.

16
00:00:50,263 --> 00:00:53,153
Obviously, you can do 
a suborbital flight from the Moon,

17
00:00:54,197 --> 00:00:58,096
just hopping up,
reaching a certain altitude,

18
00:00:58,097 --> 00:00:59,386
and then coming back down,

19
00:00:59,387 --> 00:01:00,886
because there's no atmosphere,

20
00:01:00,887 --> 00:01:03,086
there's no boundary of space,

21
00:01:03,087 --> 00:01:06,066
like is the case for the Earth
or any planet for that matter

22
00:01:06,067 --> 00:01:07,317
which has an atmosphere.

23
00:01:07,907 --> 00:01:10,777
And let's look at the profile
on the left-hand side.

24
00:01:12,013 --> 00:01:16,742
The spacecraft is either
taking off by its own means --

25
00:01:16,743 --> 00:01:18,827
we'll see some examples later--

26
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:22,449
or carried to a certain altitude
within the atmosphere

27
00:01:22,450 --> 00:01:24,019
by a carrier aircraft.

28
00:01:24,020 --> 00:01:26,939
Then it fires a rocket engine

29
00:01:26,940 --> 00:01:28,820
and goes up nearly vertically.

30
00:01:30,001 --> 00:01:34,000
A little bit shy
of the 100 kilometers boundary,

31
00:01:34,001 --> 00:01:36,041
we have a cut-off of the engine.

32
00:01:39,030 --> 00:01:43,209
And then, this part of the trajectory
is nearly parabolic.

33
00:01:43,210 --> 00:01:48,261
In fact, it's elliptic trajectory
with the center of the Earth

34
00:01:48,262 --> 00:01:49,794
being at one of the focus,

35
00:01:49,794 --> 00:01:51,284
but it is nearly parabolic.

36
00:01:51,753 --> 00:01:55,542
Then, there is typically
a few minutes of weightlessness.

37
00:01:55,543 --> 00:01:58,303
So the spacecraft is just on free-fall.

38
00:01:59,413 --> 00:02:02,372
It comes down back in the atmosphere.

39
00:02:02,373 --> 00:02:07,242
Then, of course, there is
the critical phase of the re-entry

40
00:02:07,243 --> 00:02:09,118
in the denser layers of the atmosphere,

41
00:02:09,119 --> 00:02:13,119
which has to be solved
by the manufacturer

42
00:02:13,125 --> 00:02:14,598
of the spaceplane.

43
00:02:14,599 --> 00:02:16,269
We'll talk about that later.

44
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:20,339
Typically, you have relatively high
G-forces when you come back,

45
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:21,839
of the order of 4Gs.

46
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:25,300
And then the flight ends up with gliding,

47
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:28,290
normally without any engine,

48
00:02:28,290 --> 00:02:30,479
to a runway--
and landing on the runway.

49
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:32,771
This is suborbital spaceflight.

50
00:02:33,941 --> 00:02:40,950
Well, in the U.S. the first manned,
or with humans on board suborbital flights

51
00:02:40,950 --> 00:02:45,220
were the first spaceflight 
of Americans in space

52
00:02:45,221 --> 00:02:49,311
that was following
the flight of Gagarin in April, 1961.

53
00:02:50,008 --> 00:02:53,458
In the U.S. we had Al Shepard,

54
00:02:53,459 --> 00:02:57,335
who did the first spaceflight
going with a Redstone rocket,

55
00:02:57,338 --> 00:03:01,758
which you see on the left-hand side,
on a suborbital flight

56
00:03:02,579 --> 00:03:05,929
reaching an altitude
of a little above 100 kilometers.

57
00:03:06,962 --> 00:03:08,601
This is Redstone 3--

58
00:03:08,602 --> 00:03:10,871
Redstone being the name of the rocket--

59
00:03:10,872 --> 00:03:13,791
and Redstone 4 was with Gus Grissom,

60
00:03:13,792 --> 00:03:15,981
whom you see on the right-hand side.

61
00:03:15,982 --> 00:03:17,891
Also a suborbital flight.

62
00:03:17,892 --> 00:03:20,892
And these were the first
spaceflights of Americans.

63
00:03:22,702 --> 00:03:23,912
A few years later,

64
00:03:24,463 --> 00:03:28,463
NASA developed 
a very fast aircraft, the X-15,

65
00:03:29,013 --> 00:03:32,852
which reached
a very high speed of about Mach 7,

66
00:03:32,853 --> 00:03:34,352
seven times the speed of sound.

67
00:03:34,353 --> 00:03:38,282
And on two occasions,
with the pilot, Joseph Walker,

68
00:03:38,283 --> 00:03:39,702
it reached space,

69
00:03:39,703 --> 00:03:43,002
an altitude of more than 100 kilometers.

70
00:03:43,003 --> 00:03:47,778
And you see this very fast plane

71
00:03:47,779 --> 00:03:49,748
with a rocket engine in the back.

72
00:03:49,749 --> 00:03:53,198
And it had a fuel tank,
